WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.283
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.056 --> 00:00:07.430
AJ JACOBS: It's
great to be here.

00:00:07.430 --> 00:00:08.410
I'm delighted.

00:00:08.410 --> 00:00:12.310
And I'm going to talk
today about three

00:00:12.310 --> 00:00:15.260
of my books-- so a
three for one deal.

00:00:15.260 --> 00:00:18.880
And as David mentioned, they
all have this common theme

00:00:18.880 --> 00:00:23.170
of self-experimentation,
trying to improve by testing.

00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:25.990
And right before the
talk-- this is probably

00:00:25.990 --> 00:00:27.440
not the way to start the talk.

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:32.270
But I was in the bathroom,
and the sign over the urinal

00:00:32.270 --> 00:00:35.920
had a little slogan,
testing rocks--

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:38.560
so all about testing your code.

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:41.890
So I was like, I'm
in the right place.

00:00:41.890 --> 00:00:44.210
The first book I
thought I'd discuss

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:47.980
was "The Year of
Living Biblically,"

00:00:47.980 --> 00:00:50.320
and this came about
because I grew up

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:52.180
with no religion at all.

00:00:52.180 --> 00:00:54.040
As I say in the
book, I'm Jewish,

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:57.190
but I'm Jewish in the same way
the Olive Garden is Italian

00:00:57.190 --> 00:00:59.140
so not very.

00:00:59.140 --> 00:01:03.610
But religion is such a
powerful force in society,

00:01:03.610 --> 00:01:05.080
and I wanted to
know more about it.

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:07.540
Why are people attracted to it?

00:01:07.540 --> 00:01:08.740
And I also had a son.

00:01:08.740 --> 00:01:10.330
I wanted to know
what to teach him,

00:01:10.330 --> 00:01:13.102
so I decided I'm going
to learn about religion.

00:01:13.102 --> 00:01:14.560
I'm going to learn
about the Bible,

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:17.350
and I'm going to try to learn
about it from the inside

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:20.800
out by living it, by
following in the footsteps

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:26.500
of our ancestors, and actually
follow as literally as possible

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:29.585
every single rule in the Bible.

00:01:29.585 --> 00:01:30.460
So that's what I did.

00:01:30.460 --> 00:01:34.060
I got a board of
spiritual advisors,

00:01:34.060 --> 00:01:40.600
so I got rabbis, and ministers,
and atheists, and scholars.

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:43.840
And I bought a stack of
Bibles, and I read through.

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:47.040
And I wrote down every
piece of advice, every rule

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:49.300
that I could find in the Bible.

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:52.060
That turned out to
be quite a long list,

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:55.510
over 700 rules and
pieces of advice.

00:01:55.510 --> 00:01:58.300
And I wanted to follow them
without picking and choosing.

00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:01.640
I said, I'm going to
go for it completely.

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:05.950
So I wanted to follow the famous
ones like the 10 commandments.

00:02:05.950 --> 00:02:08.650
Love your neighbor,
that's a solid one.

00:02:08.650 --> 00:02:11.440
But I also wanted to follow
the less famous rules,

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:14.410
the obscure ones, that
don't get a lot of press.

00:02:14.410 --> 00:02:18.340
The Bible says in Leviticus
that you should not

00:02:18.340 --> 00:02:21.250
shave the corners of
your beard, and I didn't

00:02:21.250 --> 00:02:22.960
know where the corners were.

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:27.670
So I thought I would just
grow the whole thing,

00:02:27.670 --> 00:02:29.400
and that's what I
looked like at the end.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:32.830
As you can see, some
serious topiary hanging

00:02:32.830 --> 00:02:37.210
from my chin and sort
of a Kaczynski vibe.

00:02:37.210 --> 00:02:40.990
And I did actually spend
quite a bit of time

00:02:40.990 --> 00:02:43.000
at airport security.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:44.530
That is true.

00:02:44.530 --> 00:02:46.900
The Bible says that
you should not wear

00:02:46.900 --> 00:02:49.060
clothes made of mixed fibers.

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:50.650
That's in Leviticus too.

00:02:50.650 --> 00:02:52.840
And I thought it
seemed a little odd.

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:58.060
It seemed a little like God
was micromanaging there,

00:02:58.060 --> 00:02:59.920
but I thought, I'm
going to follow it

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:01.150
because that's what it says.

00:03:01.150 --> 00:03:04.710
The Bible says in the Hebrew
scriptures-- many times,

00:03:04.710 --> 00:03:08.500
it says that you should stone
adulterers, and I thought, OK.

00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:10.360
I should at least try.

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:12.580
And I was able to stone one.

00:03:12.580 --> 00:03:15.630
I'll just give you an example.

00:03:15.630 --> 00:03:17.416
It was in the
middle of the year,

00:03:17.416 --> 00:03:18.790
and I was really
getting into it.

00:03:18.790 --> 00:03:19.940
So I had--

00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:23.950
I was wearing the robe and
the sandals as you can see.

00:03:23.950 --> 00:03:26.620
The sheep, that I didn't have.

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:29.440
That was a rental sheep
just for the photo--

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:30.760
but everything else.

00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:34.340
And I was in the park
here in New York,

00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:36.299
and this man came up to me.

00:03:36.299 --> 00:03:38.090
And he said, why are
you dressed like that?

00:03:38.090 --> 00:03:42.190
And I explained, I'm trying to
follow every rule in the Bible

00:03:42.190 --> 00:03:44.890
from the 10 commandments
to stoning adulterers.

00:03:44.890 --> 00:03:47.050
And he said, well,
I'm an adulterer.

00:03:47.050 --> 00:03:48.400
Are you going to stone me?

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:50.525
And I said, well, that
would be fantastic.

00:03:50.525 --> 00:03:53.080
I said, thank you
for this offer.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:55.930
And I took out a
handful of stones

00:03:55.930 --> 00:03:59.020
that I had been carrying
around in my pocket for just

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:01.090
this opportunity,
and they were small.

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:01.960
They were pebbles.

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:05.980
So I showed it to him, and I
said, you know, it's not big.

00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:07.440
He was very aggressive.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:11.920
He grabbed the stones out of my
hand and threw them at my face,

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:15.320
so I thought an eye for an
eye is also in the Bible.

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:17.470
And I threw one back at him.

00:04:17.470 --> 00:04:19.600
So that's how I
checked it off list.

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:22.720
Now at the end of the
year, I put down my stones.

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:25.180
I shaved my beard.

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:30.790
But I will say that there were
some life-changing insights I

00:04:30.790 --> 00:04:33.600
got from this and
some takeaways,

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:35.080
and there are dozens of them.

00:04:35.080 --> 00:04:38.150
But I'll just give you a couple.

00:04:38.150 --> 00:04:42.400
One is the idea of gratitude,
because the Bible says

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:44.080
that you should be thankful.

00:04:44.080 --> 00:04:46.040
So I took this literally,
and I was like,

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:48.140
I'm going to be
thankful for everything.

00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:49.960
So I would press
the elevator button.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:51.760
I'd be thankful
the elevator came.

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:52.840
I'd get in the elevator.

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:55.210
I'd be thankful it didn't
plummet to the basement

00:04:55.210 --> 00:04:56.440
and break my collarbone.

00:04:56.440 --> 00:05:00.250
So this is hundreds of times
a day I was being thankful,

00:05:00.250 --> 00:05:01.900
and it was a
strange way to live.

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:04.930
But it was also wonderful,
because it really emphasized

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:08.150
the fact that hundreds of
things go right every day

00:05:08.150 --> 00:05:11.240
that we take for granted, and
we focus on the three or four

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:13.250
that go wrong, or
at least I did.

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:15.600
So it's a radical
shift in perspective,

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:19.550
and actually it
inspired my next book

00:05:19.550 --> 00:05:22.400
which I just finished
writing yesterday,

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:23.900
only eight months late.

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:27.020
So I'm proud of myself for that.

00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:29.690
And that book, the
premise is I take

00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:32.930
one of my great joys, my
morning cup of coffee,

00:05:32.930 --> 00:05:37.070
and I try to thank every single
person who made it possible--

00:05:37.070 --> 00:05:38.420
so the barista of course.

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:41.300
But I flew to South
America, and I thanked

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:42.800
the people who grew the beans--

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:44.205
you know, the people who--

00:05:44.205 --> 00:05:46.830
the truck driver, the people who
made the truck, the people who

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:48.663
made the steel for the
truck, the people who

00:05:48.663 --> 00:05:50.150
got the iron to make the steel.

00:05:50.150 --> 00:05:53.270
And as David and I were talking
about, it's exponential.

00:05:53.270 --> 00:05:54.830
So the idea is
there are thousands

00:05:54.830 --> 00:05:59.180
of people that contribute
to every little thing we do,

00:05:59.180 --> 00:06:01.820
and we take it for granted.

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:04.950
So it's, again,
about connection.

00:06:04.950 --> 00:06:07.640
The second lesson
from this Bible book

00:06:07.640 --> 00:06:12.920
was the power of action,
the power of behavior

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:14.900
to shape your thoughts.

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:16.610
There's a great quote
from the founder

00:06:16.610 --> 00:06:17.820
of Habitat for Humanity.

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:20.900
He says, "it's easier
to act your way

00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:23.450
into a new way of thinking
than to think your way

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:24.760
into a new way of acting."

00:06:24.760 --> 00:06:27.835
It's sort of basic cognitive
behavioral psychology.

00:06:27.835 --> 00:06:31.910
You act as if you're happy
or act as if you're kind,

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:35.270
and eventually your
mind will catch up.

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:40.490
For instance, compassion,
it's not an emotion

00:06:40.490 --> 00:06:42.510
that comes naturally to me.

00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:45.920
I have some but not
very strong, so I

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:47.390
had to build it up for this.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:50.960
So I would-- my friend
was in the hospital.

00:06:50.960 --> 00:06:51.970
I hate hospitals.

00:06:51.970 --> 00:06:53.530
I didn't want to
go, but I was like,

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:54.730
what would a good person do?

00:06:54.730 --> 00:06:56.377
What would a good friend do?

00:06:56.377 --> 00:06:56.960
They would go.

00:06:56.960 --> 00:07:01.400
So I forced myself to
visit the hospital,

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:02.520
and it tricked my mind.

00:07:02.520 --> 00:07:04.880
I was like, oh, I'm in
the hospital visiting

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:05.900
a sick friend.

00:07:05.900 --> 00:07:08.540
I must be quite compassionate.

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:10.610
And my mind-- you
do that enough,

00:07:10.610 --> 00:07:11.900
and your mind catches up.

00:07:11.900 --> 00:07:16.500
It's sort of the fake it
till you become it idea.

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:19.310
And then the final
takeaway I'll mention today

00:07:19.310 --> 00:07:26.690
is the absurdity and delusion
of fundamentalist thinking,

00:07:26.690 --> 00:07:29.300
because part of the
motivation for this book

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:33.230
was to expose the
absurdity of fundamentalism

00:07:33.230 --> 00:07:36.050
by becoming the
ultimate fundamentalist

00:07:36.050 --> 00:07:38.900
and taking the
Bible at its word.

00:07:38.900 --> 00:07:42.800
Because I do find it disturbing
that, by some measure,

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:46.760
40% of America, millions
and millions of people,

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:48.590
say they take the
Bible literally,

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:51.740
and that's why they believe
homosexuality is a sin.

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:54.920
That's why they believe the
Earth is 5,000 years old.

00:07:54.920 --> 00:07:57.560
I mean, this is a tremendous
number of Americans.

00:07:57.560 --> 00:08:00.710
And it seemed to me they were
taking parts of the Bible

00:08:00.710 --> 00:08:04.130
literally, but they
were very selective.

00:08:04.130 --> 00:08:06.170
They were cherry picking,
and they were not

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:07.400
taking the bible literally.

00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:10.370
They were not wearing--

00:08:10.370 --> 00:08:13.070
avoiding clothes
made of mixed fibers.

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:17.840
So I wanted to show that if you
do take the Bible completely

00:08:17.840 --> 00:08:20.550
literally, then you're going
to act like a crazy person,

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:21.980
and it is not a good idea.

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:25.490
And that we all have to
acknowledge that when

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:27.440
we engage in ancient
texts like this

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:28.950
that we are picking
and choosing,

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:33.710
and we are doing
cafeteria style religion.

00:08:33.710 --> 00:08:36.350
We are cherry picking,
and that, listen--

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:38.150
that's fine if you pick
the right cherries.

00:08:38.150 --> 00:08:40.580
If you pick the cherries
of compassion and loving

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:43.130
your neighbor, great,
but you can also

00:08:43.130 --> 00:08:46.910
pick the rotten
cherries of hating

00:08:46.910 --> 00:08:48.320
those who are not like you.

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:56.900
The second book I'll talk
about today was about--

00:08:56.900 --> 00:08:59.180
was called "Drop Dead Healthy."

00:08:59.180 --> 00:09:00.560
And so, this was not my spirit.

00:09:00.560 --> 00:09:02.180
This was about the body.

00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:05.540
And this came about
because for most of my life

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:06.770
I've been in terrible shape.

00:09:09.410 --> 00:09:11.480
So I was what you call--

00:09:11.480 --> 00:09:13.400
I wasn't traditionally fat.

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:16.247
I was sort of skinny fat,
so I looked like a snake

00:09:16.247 --> 00:09:17.330
that had swallowed a goat.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.580
And I got sick all the time
like, literally, every week.

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:25.190
And my wife said,
you know, I don't

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:26.900
want to be a widow in my 40s.

00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:28.220
You've got to get in shape.

00:09:28.220 --> 00:09:31.550
So I decided to do what
I did for the Bible book,

00:09:31.550 --> 00:09:35.630
and I was going to test
out every single piece

00:09:35.630 --> 00:09:37.550
of medical advice I could find.

00:09:37.550 --> 00:09:40.580
I got a board of
medical advisors--

00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:43.520
doctors, nutritionist,
trainers, geneticists.

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:46.190
And I wrote down every piece
of advice I could find--

00:09:46.190 --> 00:09:49.010
again, even longer than
the Bible-- hundreds

00:09:49.010 --> 00:09:50.560
of pieces of advice.

00:09:50.560 --> 00:09:52.010
And from the next--

00:09:52.010 --> 00:09:54.980
it was supposed to be a year,
but I was such a fixer upper,

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:56.150
it took at least two years.

00:09:56.150 --> 00:09:59.090
So for the next two
years, I tried everything,

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:00.470
and it consumed my life.

00:10:00.470 --> 00:10:03.200
Because if you're trying to
follow every piece of advice,

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:05.370
like there's no time.

00:10:05.370 --> 00:10:06.410
You can't have a job.

00:10:06.410 --> 00:10:09.940
You guys have to quit
Google, because there's

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:12.670
aerobic exercise,
anaerobic exercise,

00:10:12.670 --> 00:10:14.060
you've got to
meditate every day.

00:10:14.060 --> 00:10:18.070
There's huge evidence on
the benefits of meditation.

00:10:18.070 --> 00:10:19.770
You should probably pet dogs.

00:10:19.770 --> 00:10:24.160
There are some solid studies
that that reduces hypertension.

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:26.170
I didn't have a dog
at the time, so I

00:10:26.170 --> 00:10:30.310
would go to the local dog park
and pet strangers' dogs which

00:10:30.310 --> 00:10:34.030
was received with
mixed reactions

00:10:34.030 --> 00:10:37.300
both from the owners and dogs.

00:10:37.300 --> 00:10:39.730
You have to put on sunscreen.

00:10:39.730 --> 00:10:42.820
If you follow the American
Dermatologist Association

00:10:42.820 --> 00:10:47.350
recommendations, you should be
putting on sunscreen every two

00:10:47.350 --> 00:10:51.580
hours, and you should
be putting on a shot

00:10:51.580 --> 00:10:53.770
glass full of sunscreen.

00:10:53.770 --> 00:10:58.270
That's like, my entire
salary would go to sunscreen.

00:10:58.270 --> 00:10:59.440
You've got to prepare food.

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:03.140
We all know processed
food is terrible for you.

00:11:03.140 --> 00:11:04.870
You've got to eat
food, and if you

00:11:04.870 --> 00:11:07.240
follow some
recommendations, you should

00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:09.820
take a long time
eating food, because we

00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:11.620
are a nation of under chewers--

00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:16.210
that we just wolf down our
food, and the danger of that

00:11:16.210 --> 00:11:18.150
is that we'll over--

00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:21.370
it's a sort of an
excuse to overeat.

00:11:21.370 --> 00:11:22.990
Because as you
might have heard, it

00:11:22.990 --> 00:11:27.220
takes 20 minutes for our stomach
to tell the brain that we're

00:11:27.220 --> 00:11:29.950
full, so if you are
scarfing food down,

00:11:29.950 --> 00:11:32.590
it doesn't have time
to send the message.

00:11:32.590 --> 00:11:34.750
And you guys need to
redesign the human body.

00:11:34.750 --> 00:11:40.040
That is-- it's got
some real problems.

00:11:40.040 --> 00:11:42.550
So anyway, you should chew.

00:11:42.550 --> 00:11:45.940
And I actually-- I found this
group, they are like hard core.

00:11:45.940 --> 00:11:48.912
They call their
movement, Chewdaism.

00:11:48.912 --> 00:11:50.620
I didn't make that
up, so don't blame me,

00:11:50.620 --> 00:11:54.580
but they say you should
chew 100 times per mouthful.

00:11:54.580 --> 00:11:55.900
So I tried this.

00:11:55.900 --> 00:11:57.400
I mean, it's insane.

00:11:57.400 --> 00:12:00.070
It's like it takes a day and
a half to eat a sandwich,

00:12:00.070 --> 00:12:02.050
and I don't recommend it.

00:12:02.050 --> 00:12:04.630
But I do think there is
some wisdom to chewing

00:12:04.630 --> 00:12:07.540
more and slowing down our food.

00:12:07.540 --> 00:12:11.080
Since I was a human guinea
pig, I tried everything.

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:12.100
I tested everything.

00:12:12.100 --> 00:12:16.840
I tested-- I took a
sleep test, of course--

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:19.390
didn't get a great night's
sleep that night shockingly.

00:12:19.390 --> 00:12:23.740
I tried every workout I
could find, including the--

00:12:23.740 --> 00:12:25.300
this is the cave man workout.

00:12:25.300 --> 00:12:28.150
The whole paleo thing
was just taking off,

00:12:28.150 --> 00:12:31.090
so we went to Central
Park and threw boulders

00:12:31.090 --> 00:12:34.210
and climbed trees.

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:38.530
And oh, I wrote the book
of course on a treadmill,

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:40.594
so it took me about--

00:12:40.594 --> 00:12:41.260
I think it was--

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:45.640
I think it was about 2,500
miles about to, like, Arizona

00:12:45.640 --> 00:12:48.070
or somewhere around there.

00:12:48.070 --> 00:12:50.770
In the end, again, I did
not adopt everything.

00:12:50.770 --> 00:12:54.210
I don't crawl around naked
in the woods anymore.

00:12:54.210 --> 00:12:59.080
But again, as always
with my experiments,

00:12:59.080 --> 00:13:02.980
I hope there is some takeaway,
some life-changing takeaway.

00:13:02.980 --> 00:13:09.130
And for this one, to me,
the best health advice

00:13:09.130 --> 00:13:11.410
is almost the simplest
health advice.

00:13:11.410 --> 00:13:14.050
I mean, it is so
basic that it can

00:13:14.050 --> 00:13:15.460
be summed up in a paragraph.

00:13:15.460 --> 00:13:18.250
Like, most health books
should just be a paragraph.

00:13:18.250 --> 00:13:19.810
And it's stuff you all know.

00:13:19.810 --> 00:13:22.570
It's like, move more, eat less--

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:28.060
eat good food, real
food, not processed food.

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:32.386
Do the, you know--

00:13:32.386 --> 00:13:34.240
don't smoke.

00:13:34.240 --> 00:13:36.480
Don't hit yourself in
the head with an ax.

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:39.700
Like, it's very basic stuff.

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:42.790
There is some evidence for high
intensity interval training,

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:45.110
so if you're into that, do that.

00:13:45.110 --> 00:13:47.380
But it's really quite
basic, and we all know it.

00:13:47.380 --> 00:13:51.810
And the mystery to me is
why we don't act healthily

00:13:51.810 --> 00:13:55.750
when we all know what
acting healthily is,

00:13:55.750 --> 00:13:58.480
and that, to me, is
where you can find

00:13:58.480 --> 00:14:01.750
some interesting insights in
how to motivate yourself--

00:14:01.750 --> 00:14:05.860
how to sort of engineer
yourself to be more healthy.

00:14:05.860 --> 00:14:09.610
And there were several
interesting strategies.

00:14:09.610 --> 00:14:12.370
I'll just give you
one that works for me,

00:14:12.370 --> 00:14:16.740
and that is it's this
idea of egonomics.

00:14:16.740 --> 00:14:20.110
That's a term coined by
a Yale professor, who

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:23.950
talks about how we all
have two selves at least.

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:26.800
We have our present self who
wants to just hang out and eat

00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:28.930
Cheetos on the couch,
and then you've

00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:32.980
got your future self who
wants that present self

00:14:32.980 --> 00:14:37.390
to get on a treadmill
or eat some salad.

00:14:37.390 --> 00:14:41.500
So we've got these two
selves that are in conflict.

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:45.100
And one of the keys to
making better decisions

00:14:45.100 --> 00:14:50.740
in every part of our life is to
try to remember our older self.

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:54.430
And I think of my older
self as some other person

00:14:54.430 --> 00:14:55.930
that I want to treat well.

00:14:55.930 --> 00:14:59.510
I want to treat that person
like I would treat a friend,

00:14:59.510 --> 00:15:01.642
and you can do this visually.

00:15:01.642 --> 00:15:03.100
And actually, you
guys can help me.

00:15:03.100 --> 00:15:08.330
Because I did find some
digital aging software,

00:15:08.330 --> 00:15:09.640
but it's not great.

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:12.760
So if you guys
have better ones--

00:15:12.760 --> 00:15:16.060
so I printed that out,
and I put it over my desk.

00:15:16.060 --> 00:15:18.850
And it does inspire
me sometimes.

00:15:18.850 --> 00:15:20.950
I'll look at it, and I'll
be like, you know what?

00:15:20.950 --> 00:15:24.610
I'm going to do this for
the older version of me, who

00:15:24.610 --> 00:15:28.130
I want that guy to be around
to see my kids grow up

00:15:28.130 --> 00:15:31.660
and, you know, get married
or not get married,

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:34.010
whatever they choose.

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:35.800
So that is just one of the ways.

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:39.310
It's all about how to
motivate yourself, I think,

00:15:39.310 --> 00:15:42.220
as opposed to what is healthy?

00:15:42.220 --> 00:15:46.060
Because people try to make a
lot of money by telling you

00:15:46.060 --> 00:15:48.310
they have the secret bullet--
you know, the blood type

00:15:48.310 --> 00:15:49.570
diet, whatever.

00:15:49.570 --> 00:15:54.580
Dr. Oz has a new cure every
day, but really science

00:15:54.580 --> 00:15:59.040
moves more slowly than that,
and we know what is healthy.

00:15:59.040 --> 00:16:01.390
All right, so the final
book I want to talk about,

00:16:01.390 --> 00:16:03.850
before opening it up to any
questions you might have,

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:07.660
is this one was started
about four years ago.

00:16:07.660 --> 00:16:12.460
This started because I got a
very strange email from a man,

00:16:12.460 --> 00:16:14.400
and he said, you
who don't know me,

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:17.110
but I am your eighth cousin.

00:16:17.110 --> 00:16:20.050
And I thought, as
you might, that he

00:16:20.050 --> 00:16:23.220
was going to ask me to wire
$10,000 to his Nigerian bank.

00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:26.550
It seemed sketchy, but it
turns out he was legitimate.

00:16:26.550 --> 00:16:29.980
And he is this man
who is obsessed

00:16:29.980 --> 00:16:34.939
with helping to build these
family trees that are big.

00:16:34.939 --> 00:16:35.980
They're not really trees.

00:16:35.980 --> 00:16:37.120
They're forests.

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:41.680
They are massive interconnected
forests and not just thousands

00:16:41.680 --> 00:16:45.130
of people, millions of people.

00:16:45.130 --> 00:16:47.320
So it's a new--

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:49.450
I always thought genealogy--

00:16:49.450 --> 00:16:53.020
kind of stodgy, sort
of in the needle point.

00:16:53.020 --> 00:16:54.402
No offense to needle point.

00:16:54.402 --> 00:16:56.360
Some people-- I once said
that, and people were

00:16:56.360 --> 00:16:57.970
like, needle point's hip now.

00:16:57.970 --> 00:16:58.720
Sorry.

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:01.240
But anyway, I just thought
it was a little stodgy.

00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:03.980
But nowadays, it's
actually not at all,

00:17:03.980 --> 00:17:08.740
and it's affecting every
part of our lives-- politics,

00:17:08.740 --> 00:17:12.160
race relations, happiness--

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:15.280
because there are these
amazing revolutions,

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:18.500
technological revolutions,
going on in the field.

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:20.260
And there are two main ones.

00:17:20.260 --> 00:17:23.109
One is these massive
family trees,

00:17:23.109 --> 00:17:25.810
where you have millions
of people connected--

00:17:25.810 --> 00:17:27.609
sort of a Wikipedia model.

00:17:27.609 --> 00:17:31.240
You put up your tree, and you
can connect it to other trees

00:17:31.240 --> 00:17:33.690
if you share a relative.

00:17:33.690 --> 00:17:35.590
And it's almost
become-- it's like

00:17:35.590 --> 00:17:37.300
the ultimate social network.

00:17:37.300 --> 00:17:39.950
It's like six degrees
of Kevin Bacon,

00:17:39.950 --> 00:17:41.470
but everyone's Kevin Bacon.

00:17:41.470 --> 00:17:44.470
And you can connect to
almost anyone in the world.

00:17:44.470 --> 00:17:46.960
Like, I'm on one tree.

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:49.750
It's got about 110
million, and I've

00:17:49.750 --> 00:17:52.330
got my cousin
Barack Obama, who is

00:17:52.330 --> 00:17:56.380
my fifth great aunt's
husband's brother's wife's

00:17:56.380 --> 00:17:57.940
seventh great nephew.

00:17:57.940 --> 00:18:01.460
So we're very close.

00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:04.840
But the idea is, as again,
we are all connected.

00:18:04.840 --> 00:18:06.470
And for the first
time in history,

00:18:06.470 --> 00:18:10.040
we can actually see
how this is happening.

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:12.070
The other revolution,
as you probably know,

00:18:12.070 --> 00:18:14.080
is genetic testing.

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:18.280
You can spit into a
tube, and send it off,

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:21.880
and get your ancestry
percentages allegedly

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:26.830
and a list of
hundreds of cousins

00:18:26.830 --> 00:18:30.070
you never knew you had
and might not want to have

00:18:30.070 --> 00:18:32.140
but there they are.

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:35.530
Now this, I was
fascinated by this,

00:18:35.530 --> 00:18:38.590
and I thought this has to be
the topic of my next book.

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:42.070
And as I got into it,
what struck me was,

00:18:42.070 --> 00:18:45.700
like all technology
revolutions, this

00:18:45.700 --> 00:18:50.150
has the potential to do
tremendous good for society.

00:18:50.150 --> 00:18:54.610
It also has potential to do
tremendous ill to society.

00:18:54.610 --> 00:18:58.690
So let me quickly go over how I
think it could be great for us,

00:18:58.690 --> 00:19:00.790
and then how it could
take a left turn

00:19:00.790 --> 00:19:03.670
and take us down
some dark alleyways.

00:19:03.670 --> 00:19:07.870
The way it could be good,
I think, is just a very--

00:19:07.870 --> 00:19:11.980
first way is just the very
simple, almost childlike fact

00:19:11.980 --> 00:19:16.060
that we're all one big family,
but now we can actually see it.

00:19:16.060 --> 00:19:19.330
You can see it
concretely, and it makes--

00:19:19.330 --> 00:19:21.410
it actually makes a difference.

00:19:21.410 --> 00:19:24.670
And the hope is that
when we realize this,

00:19:24.670 --> 00:19:27.400
we will treat each other
with a little more kindness

00:19:27.400 --> 00:19:30.070
or at least a little
less horribleness.

00:19:30.070 --> 00:19:33.730
And there is some empirical
evidence that this is true.

00:19:33.730 --> 00:19:35.920
There was a Harvard
study a year ago,

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:39.730
where they took
Palestinians and Israelis,

00:19:39.730 --> 00:19:42.700
and they told one
group that they were--

00:19:42.700 --> 00:19:45.620
they showed them how they
were related, and the other,

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:46.990
they didn't.

00:19:46.990 --> 00:19:49.390
And that test
group, that knew how

00:19:49.390 --> 00:19:52.630
they were related to each
other, treated the other group

00:19:52.630 --> 00:19:53.670
with more kindness.

00:19:53.670 --> 00:19:58.480
They didn't buzz them as
loudly on a memory test,

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:01.880
so there is some evidence
that it might work,

00:20:01.880 --> 00:20:05.330
this idea of we're
all family, then

00:20:05.330 --> 00:20:07.040
we should be kinder
to each other.

00:20:07.040 --> 00:20:09.150
I see it on a personal level.

00:20:09.150 --> 00:20:12.650
This is not quite as profound
as Palestinians and Arabs,

00:20:12.650 --> 00:20:19.620
but for instance, I always hated
Judge Judy, the personality.

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:21.170
I just thought
she was obnoxious,

00:20:21.170 --> 00:20:23.990
and nasty, and not that smart.

00:20:23.990 --> 00:20:26.840
But then I saw that
she's my eighth cousin,

00:20:26.840 --> 00:20:30.510
and it actually had, rationally
or not, it had an effect.

00:20:30.510 --> 00:20:32.870
I was like, oh,
she's not so bad.

00:20:32.870 --> 00:20:33.966
She's just cousin Judy.

00:20:33.966 --> 00:20:35.090
She's just doing a schtick.

00:20:35.090 --> 00:20:36.920
She's probably a
sweetheart underneath.

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:41.590
And so, my hope is that this
Judge Judy effect will be good.

00:20:41.590 --> 00:20:44.050
The second way I
hope it will be good

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:50.330
is that it will expose
this myth of racial purity.

00:20:50.330 --> 00:20:53.510
And one of my advisors for
this was Henry Louis Gates,

00:20:53.510 --> 00:20:57.410
the Harvard professor, and
that's one of his big themes--

00:20:57.410 --> 00:21:00.050
is there's no such
thing as racial purity.

00:21:00.050 --> 00:21:01.040
We are all a mix.

00:21:01.040 --> 00:21:05.450
We are all mutts,
and that's good.

00:21:05.450 --> 00:21:08.810
And there are some
interesting phenomena

00:21:08.810 --> 00:21:13.370
happening, where white
supremacists take these tests,

00:21:13.370 --> 00:21:16.160
and then they find
out, some of them,

00:21:16.160 --> 00:21:21.570
that they have African-American
or Jewish heritage.

00:21:21.570 --> 00:21:23.540
And the reactions
are mixed of course.

00:21:23.540 --> 00:21:25.350
Some deny it.

00:21:25.350 --> 00:21:27.860
They say, oh, 23andMe
is a big conspiracy,

00:21:27.860 --> 00:21:30.230
a multicultural conspiracy.

00:21:30.230 --> 00:21:33.110
But some actually have this
change of heart, and like, oh,

00:21:33.110 --> 00:21:33.950
you know what?

00:21:33.950 --> 00:21:37.160
My world view may
not be that accurate.

00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:41.800
So the hope is that
this will increase.

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:45.050
And I, myself,
took all the tests.

00:21:45.050 --> 00:21:46.760
I took six or seven of them.

00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:49.340
They all reveal I
was mostly Jewish,

00:21:49.340 --> 00:21:51.540
but they had different nuances.

00:21:51.540 --> 00:21:53.470
One said, which was
interesting, I thought,

00:21:53.470 --> 00:22:00.560
I am 97% Ashkenazi Jew
but 2.5% Egyptian-Arab.

00:22:00.560 --> 00:22:06.890
So I liked having the Middle
East conflict in my body.

00:22:06.890 --> 00:22:09.350
The final way I think
that it could be good

00:22:09.350 --> 00:22:12.620
is that it could broaden
the idea of family,

00:22:12.620 --> 00:22:14.790
because this idea of
the nuclear family,

00:22:14.790 --> 00:22:18.040
the two parents and the
two kids, is actually not--

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:20.090
it's a pretty new concept.

00:22:20.090 --> 00:22:23.360
When industrialization came
and people moved to the city

00:22:23.360 --> 00:22:25.370
to be away from their
extended family,

00:22:25.370 --> 00:22:27.830
that's when that idea that
this is the normal family

00:22:27.830 --> 00:22:28.640
came about.

00:22:28.640 --> 00:22:31.070
It's not really
the normal family.

00:22:31.070 --> 00:22:33.530
And I like the idea of
broadening the family

00:22:33.530 --> 00:22:38.990
to include gay marriage, sperm
donors, open adoption, even

00:22:38.990 --> 00:22:41.680
group families.

00:22:41.680 --> 00:22:45.260
And one of my favorite
stories in the book is--

00:22:45.260 --> 00:22:49.400
I've found these twins,
separated at birth twins.

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:51.020
They were born in Korea.

00:22:51.020 --> 00:22:52.280
They moved.

00:22:52.280 --> 00:22:55.940
They were both adopted by
families in the United States,

00:22:55.940 --> 00:22:58.100
and they didn't know
about each other.

00:22:58.100 --> 00:23:01.790
But they had a mutual
acquaintance on Facebook

00:23:01.790 --> 00:23:05.420
who said, you guys
look weirdly similar--

00:23:05.420 --> 00:23:07.460
like, same freckles even.

00:23:07.460 --> 00:23:10.230
And they got together,
and they took a DNA test.

00:23:10.230 --> 00:23:14.840
It turned out they
were sisters, and it

00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:16.700
blew their minds of course.

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:19.160
They tried to contact
their biological mom.

00:23:19.160 --> 00:23:21.320
She didn't want anything
to do with it, which--

00:23:21.320 --> 00:23:22.470
so that's the sad part.

00:23:22.470 --> 00:23:27.440
The uplifting part,
to me, is that she--

00:23:27.440 --> 00:23:31.460
one of the sisters told me I
feel like I have lots of moms.

00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:33.200
I have an abundance of moms.

00:23:33.200 --> 00:23:37.310
I've got my adoptive mom,
my twin's adoptive mom--

00:23:37.310 --> 00:23:40.580
she's an actress, and so she
has what she calls a momager.

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:48.440
So this idea of reconceiving
family not just as strict DNA.

00:23:48.440 --> 00:23:50.630
One writer says--
he calls it there's

00:23:50.630 --> 00:23:54.470
your biological family
and your logical family.

00:23:54.470 --> 00:23:58.610
And I think that's a good thing
to expand the idea of family,

00:23:58.610 --> 00:24:01.610
because as my eighth cousin,
Hillary Clinton, said,

00:24:01.610 --> 00:24:04.320
it takes a village.

00:24:04.320 --> 00:24:06.970
All right, and then
quickly I'll end.

00:24:06.970 --> 00:24:10.760
I like to end on a
down note on the ways

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:13.690
it could be terrible
for society.

00:24:13.690 --> 00:24:17.930
So my main hope, of course, is
that it decreases tribalism,

00:24:17.930 --> 00:24:20.240
which I think is one of the--

00:24:20.240 --> 00:24:23.370
it's sort of the
problem of all problems,

00:24:23.370 --> 00:24:26.030
because if we cannot
cooperate as a species,

00:24:26.030 --> 00:24:30.390
we cannot solve these worldwide
problems like climate change.

00:24:30.390 --> 00:24:33.140
So hopefully, it will
decrease, but there

00:24:33.140 --> 00:24:35.210
is a chance it'll
do just the opposite

00:24:35.210 --> 00:24:37.220
and increase tribalism.

00:24:37.220 --> 00:24:40.580
I talked to one
sociologist at Princeton,

00:24:40.580 --> 00:24:44.750
who, that's his greatest
fear-- is that these DNA tests,

00:24:44.750 --> 00:24:46.730
everyone will get
their DNA tests

00:24:46.730 --> 00:24:50.480
and go into their
own little silos,

00:24:50.480 --> 00:24:52.370
their little ethnic silos.

00:24:52.370 --> 00:24:59.180
And his nightmare scenario is
sort of a 23andMe meets Tinder.

00:24:59.180 --> 00:25:05.460
So you like-- you know,
you're 72% Scandinavian.

00:25:05.460 --> 00:25:08.160
You will only date
people who also are

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:10.950
70% Scandinavian and above--

00:25:10.950 --> 00:25:14.130
and that it will
sort of turn the tide

00:25:14.130 --> 00:25:17.940
against the decades long
trend of intermarriage

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:19.390
between groups.

00:25:19.390 --> 00:25:22.930
So that is one
potential downside.

00:25:22.930 --> 00:25:23.820
There is also--

00:25:23.820 --> 00:25:28.020
I mean, it's going to be
psychologically traumatic

00:25:28.020 --> 00:25:33.190
for some people, because an
estimated 2% of the world,

00:25:33.190 --> 00:25:34.470
and that's a lot of people--

00:25:34.470 --> 00:25:37.320
you guys are better at math,
so you know how much it is,

00:25:37.320 --> 00:25:38.910
but that's a lot of people.

00:25:38.910 --> 00:25:42.720
And 2% of those
are what are called

00:25:42.720 --> 00:25:46.560
euphemistically
non-paternal events, which

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:50.640
means that their father
is someone else that they

00:25:50.640 --> 00:25:52.660
don't know about.

00:25:52.660 --> 00:25:56.850
And so, we're going to
see an increasing number.

00:25:56.850 --> 00:25:58.350
The world is going
to be like one

00:25:58.350 --> 00:26:03.240
big "Maury Povich" show as
people discover, more and more,

00:26:03.240 --> 00:26:05.250
that they have a father.

00:26:05.250 --> 00:26:09.610
And it all depends on how we
react to that information.

00:26:09.610 --> 00:26:13.700
I have a chapter in my book
about a guy who, as an adult,

00:26:13.700 --> 00:26:15.090
he has nine siblings.

00:26:15.090 --> 00:26:18.450
He lived in the Midwest,
and they took DNA tests.

00:26:18.450 --> 00:26:23.090
And it turned out every single
one of those nine siblings

00:26:23.090 --> 00:26:27.970
was from a different
father, and the biological,

00:26:27.970 --> 00:26:31.380
the assumed father,
was biologically

00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:33.840
the dad of none of them--

00:26:33.840 --> 00:26:39.600
so again, like "Maury
Povich" times exponentially.

00:26:39.600 --> 00:26:41.940
And it was interesting,
the reaction,

00:26:41.940 --> 00:26:46.410
because some of the
siblings were understandably

00:26:46.410 --> 00:26:48.090
horrified and upset.

00:26:48.090 --> 00:26:51.650
You know, my mother is a
tramp, et cetera, et cetera.

00:26:51.650 --> 00:26:54.540
But some-- hey, the one
I interviewed actually

00:26:54.540 --> 00:26:57.480
tried to reframe it and
be like, oh, this is nice.

00:26:57.480 --> 00:27:00.960
I have all of these
new half siblings.

00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:07.910
So it's a lot about how we
react to this information.

00:27:07.910 --> 00:27:08.700
Oh, I will end.

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:11.460
Actually, I'm going to end on
a slightly more positive note,

00:27:11.460 --> 00:27:15.240
because the book is partly about
explaining these revolutions.

00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:20.670
Partly it's a memoir of my
own delightfully odd family.

00:27:20.670 --> 00:27:23.530
I'm very grateful I
have a strange family.

00:27:23.530 --> 00:27:28.980
And partly it's this adventure,
because this was about two

00:27:28.980 --> 00:27:31.200
years ago, I decided--

00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:34.470
since I have all these
cousins, I will try to put on--

00:27:34.470 --> 00:27:36.390
why not have a party?

00:27:36.390 --> 00:27:39.300
Why not have a family
reunion for all

00:27:39.300 --> 00:27:41.730
of my seven billion cousins?

00:27:41.730 --> 00:27:43.320
So I did invite seven billion.

00:27:43.320 --> 00:27:47.120
