there are some good books.

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:10.550
Marion Nestle-- Marion
Nestle is a nutritionist

00:41:10.550 --> 00:41:14.100
who has a good book
called "What to Eat."

00:41:14.100 --> 00:41:20.330
I think you don't even need a
book on exercise, because aside

00:41:20.330 --> 00:41:24.110
from the idea of--

00:41:24.110 --> 00:41:26.810
I do think there is some
evidence that high intensity

00:41:26.810 --> 00:41:30.560
interval training like going
really hard for two minutes

00:41:30.560 --> 00:41:32.840
has some benefits,
but mostly it's

00:41:32.840 --> 00:41:35.870
just do exercise--
you know, just

00:41:35.870 --> 00:41:38.490
whatever you find pleasurable,
because you're never

00:41:38.490 --> 00:41:40.490
going to do it if you
don't find it pleasurable.

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:42.990
So it could be gardening, it
could be building a stone wall,

00:41:42.990 --> 00:41:44.750
or whatever.

00:41:44.750 --> 00:41:48.410
So anyway, those
are my thoughts.

00:41:48.410 --> 00:41:52.370
I mean, I think one of the
big problems with health right

00:41:52.370 --> 00:41:57.920
now is the health media,
because of the biases built

00:41:57.920 --> 00:42:02.390
into journalism, you want
the man bites dog story.

00:42:02.390 --> 00:42:05.390
You want the-- if you
find one study that

00:42:05.390 --> 00:42:09.140
says bacon is great for
you, that's the headline.

00:42:09.140 --> 00:42:10.880
That's the article
you're going to write,

00:42:10.880 --> 00:42:17.360
not the 980 studies that said
bacon is not good for you.

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:25.420
So it's this sort of unusual
study syndrome and flaw

00:42:25.420 --> 00:42:28.520
that I think is super
dangerous, and that we

00:42:28.520 --> 00:42:30.560
need more perspective.

00:42:30.560 --> 00:42:32.330
There needs to be context.

00:42:32.330 --> 00:42:35.720
I think of it as the Rotten
Tomatoes of health advice.

00:42:35.720 --> 00:42:37.970
You know, you're
always going to find

00:42:37.970 --> 00:42:44.250
a critic who loves "Battlestar
Earth," but 99% of them

00:42:44.250 --> 00:42:44.750
are not.

00:42:44.750 --> 00:42:47.780
So you're always going to
find a scientist who says--

00:42:47.780 --> 00:42:50.570
with good credentials--
who says, you know,

00:42:50.570 --> 00:42:55.160
that you should only eat
broccoli if you have blood

00:42:55.160 --> 00:42:59.120
type, C. Is there a blood
type, C I don't think there--

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:02.830
blood type, B. But that is--

00:43:02.830 --> 00:43:05.000
that is an outlier,
so you got to look

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:09.260
at what the mass of the
scientific community says

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:10.482
and go with that.

